Problem Statement: AllLife Credit Card Customer Segmentation¶

Objective¶

  • To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

Attribute details¶

  • Sl_No
  • Customer Key
  • Avg_Credit_Limit
  • Total_Credit_Cards
  • Total_visits_bank
  • Total_visits_online
  • Total_calls_made

Grouping Data into similar clusters¶

  • Trying K-Means clustering to group data based on their attributes.
  • Using Elbow method to determine the optimal number of groups.
In [16]:
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist

clusters_range= range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]


for clusters in clusters_range:
    model= KMeans(n_clusters= clusters,random_state=20)
    model.fit(df_Scaled)
    prediction= model.predict(df_Scaled)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(df_Scaled, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / df_Scaled.shape[0])
   
plt.plot(clusters_range, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
Out[16]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
  • Elbow method to determine number of clusters
  • Elbow can be considered to be around K=3 or K=4
  • Lets take K=3 and rebuild model
In [17]:
# Checking SilHouette Scores
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
scores=[]

for clusters in range(2,11):
    model= KMeans(n_clusters= clusters,random_state=20)
    model.fit(df_Scaled)
    prediction= model.predict(df_Scaled)
    print('silhouette_score for', clusters,' cluster is :' ,silhouette_score(df_Scaled,prediction))
    scores.append(silhouette_score(df_Scaled,prediction))

from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import cophenet, dendrogram, linkage
In [35]:
from scipy.spatial.distance import pdist  #Pairwise distribution between data points
In [36]:
# cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram
# closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering

Z = linkage(df_Scaled, metric='euclidean', method='average')
c_Avg, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(df_Scaled))

c_Avg

x_cor=range(0,5)        # range of X co-ordinate [0,1,2,3,4]
y_cor=range(0,3)        # range of Y co-ordinate [0,1,2]
cols = ['Avg_Credit_Limit', 'Total_Credit_Cards', 'Total_visits_bank','Total_visits_online', 'Total_calls_made']
color=['r', 'b', 'g']
a=0
fig,ax=plt.subplots(5,3,figsize=(20,20))
for i in x_cor:
    s=0                             # This variable is used to increment cluster/ label number
    for j in y_cor:
        col=cols[a]
        clr=color[s]
        cluster=df_Attr[df_Attr['labels']==s]
        sns.distplot(cluster[col],color=clr,ax=ax[i][j],kde=False, axlabel=('{} {} {}'.format(col,'- Cluster', j)))
        s=s+1
    a=a+1

Cluster Analysis¶

  • There are three clusters formed
  • Number of Customers in Cluster 0 : 397, Cluster 1 : 50, Cluster 2 : 213
  • Cluster 1 customers are having high Average Credit Limit
  • Cluster 1 customers are having more number of Credit cards
  • Looking to Cluster 1 Customers Credit Limit and holding Credit card numbers, we can infer that they are from segement whose expenditure are high.
  • Bank should Target to increase customers in Cluster 1
  • Bank should target to check if there is potential issue in Cluster 0, 2 to increase their Credit Limit
